[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Assessing testing approach**\n\nI’m considering the ByteBufferWriter being package-private. It’s interesting to think about whether behavior is supported through the library's internal structure. Maybe it's best to focus on testing class initialization at the specific call sites. However, that doesn't seem to cover behavior. To access the active class, I'd use Class.forName for static initialization and getDeclaredField. But the tests might not satisfy with only no-op class literals or assertions that reference metadata targets.\n\n**Evaluating coding standards**\n\nI’m thinking about how class name assertions are not ideal. Instead, using method handles to invoke writes and assert outputs—like in protobuf tests—would be better. The approach involves static initialization and behavior, along with reflection to access package-private methods. However, maybe it's acceptable for internal package-private classes where other options fail. I'll also consider the import order: should static imports come last? I need to check the existing project’s style and maybe follow conventional standards too.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0e6136cdc9afed8b016a222c731ae48193a6893f3d07d247f3\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqIiyFTV_tSLGTmQrQhTRXllaUcjSpxA7dHd3ixDj1LQn_LJ5POowp3_sFhteyNSW1bAof7652zEFJZ6tcKJqLWurW1kKKdshiIAHir5JI4h-zEzQceumVU8NI_ouIZPouku2TuWFD2EgoaBDuXBKfpI4BS3xCiG8gh__OJGiY93PEOLqesbS_1pQ-t4cJufVI6HVp_6Z89LLMan-fYyj5A-Jt7xNWOwa7ceH7LTHwK7fvbGttOwMkDihXuX0P1VfU3St4fXZ93WIfT_k2TWzXqX--tpyXnl1YPmfAQanNXyH2ppM07HW2wMO5uWZtN6pOBPdwkIy-assZvwEQx8p6rjw9_ypq2I-h4zqAk1ETJ0lAqub_cd_Hzenx4gGmfxSdlG9RJzSJVZfLXf5R7tPE_114KR7YiO1qfNJfnHe0JqZGCUQeb432CgdcDsFknbYsxMNfeeehmL7DR3Mut_MHUelxr0gNveiho9Xcu9uWNknJ8OklqNgTBAh7P27uoqYmyzUKm1AK3bcP4GbXkzu2Er5GecnpSTwLhPu-qsJFj4b0JMH_1IXcIYciiPxg2y-ueS4Ll4D8gLBlGfheBLuUrhhStK23iaik16BS1d5-O3NLj2N